": "ViceAdmiral", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/12_Motorised_Infantry_Brigade_(Namibia)"}
{"title_page": "Diet food", "text_new": "{{More citations needed|date=May 2008}}\n[[File:Penne with eggplant and basil in yogurt-tomato sauce.jpg|thumb|[[Penne]] with [[eggplant]] and [[basil]] in yogurt-[[tomato sauce]]. Dish is a part of cookbook for women with [[Gestational diabetes]].]]\n[[File:New KM.jpg|thumb|right|A \"low fat\" child's meal from [[Burger King]], with \"apple fries\" replacing fried potato chips, and a serving of [[macaroni and cheese]] as its main dish]]\n'''Diet food''' (or '''dietetic food''') refers to any food or beverage whose recipe is altered to reduce fat, carbohydrates, and/or sugar in order to make it part of a weight loss program or [http://www.zaysan.com/category/health-fitness/weight-loss/ diet.] Such foods are usually intended to assist in weight loss or a change in body type, although [[bodybuilding supplements]] are designed to aid in gaining weight or muscle.\nFoods less than 100 calories do not require the use of nutrition labels however may choose to do so.\n\n==Terminology==\nIn addition to ''diet'' other words or phrases are used to identify and describe these foods including ''light'', ''zero calorie'', ''low calorie'', ''low fat'', ''no fat'' and ''sugar free''. In some areas use of these terms may be regulated by law. For example, in the U.S. a product labeled as \"low fat\" must not contain more than 3 grams of fat per serving; and to be labeled \"fat free\" it must contain less than 0.5 grams of fat per serving.<ref>[https://www.thenutritionalsource.com/definitions-of-nutrient-content-claims/ Definitions of Nutrient Content Claims], [[U.S. Food and Drug Administration]] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161005192448/https://www.thenutritionalsource.com/definitions-of-nutrient-content-claims/ |date=October 5, 2016 }}</ref>\n\n==Process==\nThe process of making a diet version of a food usually requires finding an acceptable low-food-energy substitute for some high-food-energy ingredient.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cdc.gov/NCCdphp/dnpa/nutrition/pdf/r2p_energy_density.pdf|title=Low-Energy-Dense Foods|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=|access-date=}}</ref> This can be as simple as replacing some or all of the food's [[sugar]] with a [[sugar substitute]] as is common with diet soft drinks such as [[Coca-Cola]] (for example [[Diet Coke]]). In some snacks, the food may be baked instead of fried thus reducing the food energy. In other cases, low-fat ingredients may be used as replacements. If you are doing on a low-fat diet, there are many benefit in this diet. Low-fat diets can help you lose weight by using calories on more filling food, and ward off serious medical conditions, including heart disease, high cholesterol, and diabetes.\n\nIn [[whole grain]] foods, the higher fiber content effectively displaces some of the starch component of the flour. Since certain fibers have no food energy, this results in a modest energy reduction. Another technique relies on the intentional addition of other reduced-food-energy ingredients, such as [[resistant starch]] or [[dietary fiber]], to replace part of the flour and achieve a more significant energy reduction.\n\n== Example of low-fat foods ==\n\nThe low-fat foods are those that have 30% of their calories or less from fats. So, if a food contains fewer than 3 gram of fat per 100 calories, it is a low fat food. Examples of cereals, grain, and pasta products are corn or whole wheat tortillas, oatmeal, backed cracker, whole grain versions of noodles, and pita bread. Examples of protein sources are beans, lentils, tofu, egg white, tuna, and peas. On the other hand, polysaturated such as omega 3 and omega 6 fatty acids can be beneficial to the body. Nutritious foods are avocado, almond, salmon, cashews, seeds, and walnuts.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.medicalnewstoday.com/articles/325860.php|title=Low fat foods: List, benefits, and meal plan|website=Medical News Today|language=en|access-date=2019-11-25}}</ref>\n\n==Controversy==\nIn diet foods<ref>[http://www.nhs.uk/livewell/goodfood/Pages/Goodfoodhome.aspx Diet and good food], National Health Service</ref> which replace the sugar with lower-food-energy substitutes, there is some controversy based around the possibility that the [[sugar substitute]]s used to replace sugar are themselves harmful.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2016/01/18/health/where-do-we-stand-artificial-sweeteners/index.html|title=Can artificial sweeteners cause weight gain?|author=Sandee LaMotte|website=CNN|access-date=2019-11-11}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://finance.yahoo.com/news/best-worst-sugar-substitutes-health-145139561.html|title=The best and worst sugar substitutes for your health|website=finance.yahoo.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-11-11}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newsweek.com/artificial-sweeteners-splenda-crohns-disease-gut-849690|title=Artificial sweeteners like Splenda may make Crohn's Disease gut issues worse, a study showed|last=EDT|first=Janissa Delzo On 3/16/18 at 4:45 PM|date=2018-03-16|website=Newsweek|language=en|access-date=2019-11-11}}</ref> Artificial sweeteners have been the subject of intense scrutiny for decades, but according to the National Cancer Institute and other health agencies, there is no sound scientific evidence that any of the artificial sweeteners approved for use in the U.S. cause cancer or other serious health problems. Numerous research studies confirm that artificial sweeteners are generally safe in limited quantities, even for pregnant women.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mayoclinic.org/healthy-living/nutrition-and-healthy-eating/in-depth/artificial-sweeteners/art-20046936 |title=Artificial sweeteners and other sugar substitutes |publisher=mayoclinic.org |date= |accessdate=2012-10-09}}</ref>\n\nIn many low-fat and fat-free foods the fat is replaced with [[sugar]], [[flour]], or other full-food-energy ingredients, and the reduction in food energy value is small, if any.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20070617121713/http://www.fda.gov/fdac/features/2002/chrt_calcomp.html Fat-Free vs. Regular Calorie Comparison], U.S. Food and Drug Administration</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Negative-calorie food]]\n*[[Olestra]]\n*[[Online weight loss plans]]\n*[[Obesity paradox]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Food science}}\n{{Diets}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Diet Food}}\n[[Category:Diets]]\n", "text_old": "{{More citations needed|date=May 2008}}\n[[File:Penne with eggplant and basil in yogurt-tomato sauce.jpg|thumb|[[Penne]] with [[eggplant]] and [[basil]] in yogurt-[[tomato sauce]]. Dish is a part of cookbook for women with [[Gestational diabetes]].]]\n[[File:New KM.jpg|thumb|right|A \"low fat\" child's meal from [[Burger King]], with \"apple fries\" replacing fried potato chips, and a serving of [[macaroni and cheese]] as its main dish]]\n'''Diet food''' (or '''dietetic food''') refers to any food or beverage whose recipe is altered to reduce fat, carbohydrates, and/or sugar in order to make it part of a weight loss program or [[Dieting|diet.]] Such foods are usually intended to assist in weight loss or a change in body type, although [[bodybuilding supplements]] are designed to aid in gaining weight or muscle.\nFoods less than 100 calories do not require the use of nutrition labels however may choose to do so.\n\n==Terminology==\nIn addition to ''diet'' other words or phrases are used to identify and describe these foods including ''light'', ''zero calorie'', ''low calorie'', ''low fat'', ''no fat'' and ''sugar free''. In some areas use of these terms may be regulated by law. For example, in the U.S. a product labeled as \"low fat\" must not contain more than 3 grams of fat per serving; and to be labeled \"fat free\" it must contain less than 0.5 grams of fat per serving.<ref>[https://www.thenutritionalsource.com/definitions-of-nutrient-content-claims/ Definitions of Nutrient Content Claims], [[U.S. Food and Drug Administration]] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161005192448/https://www.thenutritionalsource.com/definitions-of-nutrient-content-claims/ |date=October 5, 2016 }}</ref>\n\n==Process==\nThe process of making a diet version of a food usually requires finding an acceptable low-food-energy substitute for some high-food-energy ingredient.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cdc.gov/NCCdphp/dnpa/nutrition/pdf/r2p_energy_density.pdf|title=Low-Energy-Dense Foods|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=|access-date=}}</ref> This can be as simple as replacing some or all of the food's [[sugar]] with a [[sugar substitute]] as is common with diet soft drinks such as [[Coca-Cola]] (for example [[Diet Coke]]). In some snacks, the food may be baked instead of fried thus reducing the food energy. In other cases, low-fat ingredients may be used as replacements. If you are doing on a low-fat diet, there are many benefit in this diet. Low-fat diets can help you lose weight by using calories on more filling food, and ward off serious medical conditions, including heart disease, high cholesterol, and diabetes.\n\nIn [[whole grain]] foods, the higher fiber content effectively displaces some of the starch component of the flour. Since certain fibers have no food energy, this results in a modest energy reduction. Another technique relies on the intentional addition of other reduced-food-energy ingredients, such as [[resistant starch]] or [[dietary fiber]], to replace part of the flour and achieve a more significant energy reduction.\n\n== Example of low-fat foods ==\n\nThe low-fat foods are those that have 30% of their calories or less from fats. So, if a food contains fewer than 3 gram of fat per 100 calories, it is a low fat food. Examples of cereals, grain, and pasta products are corn or whole wheat tortillas, oatmeal, backed cracker, whole grain versions of noodles, and pita bread. Examples of protein sources are beans, lentils, tofu, egg white, tuna, and peas. On the other hand, polysaturated such as omega 3 and omega 6 fatty acids can be beneficial to the body. Nutritious foods are avocado, almond, salmon, cashews, seeds, and walnuts.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.medicalnewstoday.com/articles/325860.php|title=Low fat foods: List, benefits, and meal plan|website=Medical News Today|language=en|access-date=2019-11-25}}</ref>\n\n==Controversy==\nIn diet foods<ref>[http://www.nhs.uk/livewell/goodfood/Pages/Goodfoodhome.aspx Diet and good food], National Health Service</ref> which replace the sugar with lower-food-energy substitutes, there is some controversy based around the possibility that the [[sugar substitute]]s used to replace sugar are themselves harmful.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2016/01/18/health/where-do-we-stand-artificial-sweeteners/index.html|title=Can artificial sweeteners cause weight gain?|author=Sandee LaMotte|website=CNN|access-date=2019-11-11}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://finance.yahoo.com/news/best-worst-sugar-substitutes-health-145139561.html|title=The best and worst sugar substitutes for your health|website=finance.yahoo.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-11-11}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newsweek.com/artificial-sweeteners-splenda-crohns-disease-gut-849690|title=Artificial sweeteners like Splenda may make Crohn's Disease gut issues worse, a study showed|last=EDT|first=Janissa Delzo On 3/16/18 at 4:45 PM|date=2018-03-16|website=Newsweek|language=en|access-date=2019-11-11}}</ref> Artificial sweeteners have been the subject of intense scrutiny for decades, but according to the National Cancer Institute and other health agencies, there is no sound scientific evidence that any of the artificial sweeteners approved for use in the U.S. cause cancer or other serious health problems. Numerous research studies confirm that artificial sweeteners are generally safe in limited quantities, even for pregnant women.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mayoclinic.org/healthy-living/nutrition-and-healthy-eating/in-depth/artificial-sweeteners/art-20046936 |title=Artificial sweeteners and other sugar substitutes |publisher=mayoclinic.org |date= |accessdate=2012-10-09}}</ref>\n\nIn many low-fat and fat-free foods the fat is replaced with [[sugar]], [[flour]], or other full-food-energy ingredients, and the reduction in food energy value is small, if any.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20070617121713/http://www.fda.gov/fdac/features/2002/chrt_calcomp.html Fat-Free vs. Regular Calorie Comparison], U.S. Food and Drug Administration</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Negative-calorie food]]\n*[[Olestra]]\n*[[Online weight loss plans]]\n*[[Obesity paradox]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Food science}}\n{{Diets}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Diet Food}}\n[[Category:Diets]]\n", "name_user": "Barouma01", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Diet_food"}
{"title_page": "Dog Tales (1958 film)", "text_new": "{{for|the weekly half-hour [[documentary television series]]|Dog Tales}}\n\n{{unreferenced|date=April 2014}}\n{{Infobox Hollywood cartoon\n| name = Dog Tales\n| image =\n| caption =\n| director = [[Robert McKimson]]\n| story = [[Tedd Pierce]]\n| animator = George Grandpre <br/> Ted Bonnicksen <br/> [[Warren Batchelder]] <br/> [[Tom Ray]]\n| layout_artist = [[Robert Gribbroek]]\n| background_artist = Richard H. Thomas\n| starring = [[Mel Blanc]]<br/> [[Robert C. Bruce]] (uncredited)<br/> [[Julie Bennett]]<br>(uncredited)\n| music = [[Milt Franklyn]]\n| producer = [[John W. Burton (animation)|John W. Burton, Sr.]]\n| distributor = [[Warner Bros. Pictures]] <br> [[The Vitaphone Corporation]]\n| released = July 26, 1958 (USA)\n| color_process = [[Technicolor]]\n| runtime = 8:00\n| language = English\n}}\n\n'''''Dog Tales''''' is a 1958 [[Warner Bros.]] [[animated cartoon]] which consists of a series of [[blackout gag]]s involving dogs (e.g., one in which a [[doberman pinscher]] viciously pinches an overweight U.S. Army private identified as \"Doberman\" (a reference to, and caricature of, the character played by [[Maurice Gosfield]] on ''[[The Phil Silvers Show]]''); and another in which the narrator can't make up his mind whether the dog pictured is a [[pointing breed|pointer]] or a [[setter]], and then finally shows a picture of a [[poinsettia|\"point-setter\"]]). A [[basset hound]] declares that she's a TV star (a reference to Cleo the Dog, from the contemporary TV sitcom ''[[The People's Choice (TV series)|The People's Choice]]''), we learn the unusual breed of a [[Newfoundland (dog)|Newfoundland]] puppy's grandfather, and a [[great dane]] named [[Victor Borge|\"Victor Barky\"]] plays the piano.<ref>http://www.warnercompanion.com/eowbcc-b.html</ref> Reused animation from [[Chuck Jones]]' ''[[Often an Orphan]]'' (1949) and [[Friz Freleng]]'s ''[[Piker's Peak]]'' (1957) is also seen here. In the former case, Charlie Dog makes a cameo - his final appearance in a Warner Bros. cartoon as well as his only cartoon to not be directed by Chuck Jones. This animated film features the voices of [[Mel Blanc]], [[Robert C. Bruce]] and [[Julie Bennett]], and was directed by [[Robert McKimson]] and written by [[Tedd Pierce]]. It was released in theaters on July 26, 1958.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|id=0051543|title=Dog Tales (1958 film)}}\n* {{Amg movie|id=150477|title=Dog Tales (1958 film)}}\n\n[[Category:1958 animated films]]\n[[Category:1958 films]]\n[[Category:1950s American animated films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Milt Franklyn]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Robert McKimson]]\n[[Category:Looney Tunes shorts]]\n[[Category:Animated films about dogs]]\n[[Category:Animation based on real people]]\n\n\n{{LooneyTunes-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{for|the weekly half-hour [[documentary television series]]|Dog Tales}}\n\n{{unreferenced|date=April 2014}}\n{{Infobox Hollywood cartoon\n| name = Dog Tales\n| image =\n| caption =\n| director = [[Robert McKimson]]\n| story = [[Tedd Pierce]]\n| animator = George Grandpre <br/> Ted Bonnicksen <br/> [[Warren Batchelder]] <br/> [[Tom Ray]]\n| layout_artist = [[Robert Gribbroek]]\n| background_artist = Richard H. Thomas\n| starring = [[Mel Blanc]]<br/> [[Robert C. Bruce]] (uncredited)<br/> [[Julie Bennett]]<br>(uncredited)\n| music = [[Milt Franklyn]]\n| producer = [[John W. Burton (animation)|John W. Burton, Sr.]]\n| distributor = [[Warner Bros. Pictures]] <br> [[The Vitaphone Corporation]]\n| released = July 26, 1958 (USA)\n| color_process = [[Technicolor]]\n| runtime = 8:00\n| language = English\n}}\n\n'''''Dog Tales''''' is a 1958 [[Warner Bros.]] [[animated cartoon]] which consists of a series of [[blackout gag]]s involving dogs (e.g., one in which a [[doberman pinscher]] viciously pinches an overweight U.S. Army private identified as \"Doberman\" (a reference to, and caricature of, the character played by [[Maurice Gosfield]] on ''[[The Phil Silvers Show]]''); and another in which the narrator can't make up his mind whether the dog pictured is a [[pointing breed|pointer]] or a [[setter]], and then finally shows a picture of a [[poinsettia|\"point-setter\"]]). A [[basset hound]] declares that she's a TV star (a reference to Cleo the Dog, from the contemporary TV sitcom ''[[The People's Choice (TV series)|The People's Choice]]''), we learn the unusual breed of a [[Newfoundland (dog)|Newfoundland]] puppy's grandfather, and a [[great dane]] named [[Victor Borge|\"Victor Barky\"]] plays the piano.<ref>http://www.warnercompanion.com/eowbcc-b.html</ref> Reused animation from [[Chuck Jones]]' ''[[Often an Orphan]]'' (1949) and [[Friz Freleng]]'s ''[[Piker's Peak]]'' (1957) is also seen here. In the former case, Charlie Dog makes a cameo - his final appearance in a Warner Bros. cartoon as well as his only cartoon to not be directed by Chuck Jones. This animated film features the voices of [[Mel Blanc]], [[Robert C. Bruce]] and [[Julie Bennett]], and was directed by [[Robert McKimson]] and written by [[Tedd Pierce]]. It was released in theaters on July 26, 1958.\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|id=0051543|title=Dog Tales (1958 film)}}\n* {{Amg movie|id=150477|title=Dog Tales (1958 film)}}\n\n[[Category:1958 animated films]]\n[[Category:1958 films]]\n[[Category:1950s American animated films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Milt Franklyn]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Robert McKimson]]\n[[Category:Looney Tunes shorts]]\n[[Category:Animated films about dogs]]\n[[Category:Animation based on real people]]\n\n\n{{LooneyTunes-stub}}\n", "name_user": "G\u00fcnniX", "label": "safe", "comment": "Reflist", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dog_Tales_(1958_film)"}
